directions.Direction: Preheat your smoker to 250 degrees. This temperature is ideal for smoking prime rib, as it will allow the meat to cook slowly and evenly, while also developing a smoky flavor.
Take the prime rib out of the refrigerator and let it sit at room temperature for about 30 minutes. This will allow the meat to warm up slightly and cook more evenly when it's in the smoker.

Once the smoker has reached the desired temperature, it's time to season the prime rib. In a small bowl, mix together the salt, pepper, and garlic powder. Rub this seasoning all over the prime rib, making sure to cover every inch of the meat.
Next, slather the seasoned prime rib with cooking oil. This will help to keep the meat moist while it's cooking, and also help to develop a crisp crust on the outside

Place the seasoned and oiled prime rib in the smoker and close the lid. Let it smoke for about 2 to 2.5 hours, or until it reaches an internal temperature of 125 degrees. You can use a meat thermometer to check the internal temperature of the meat, inserting it into the thickest part of the roast.

While the prime rib is smoking, you can start preparing the golden potato fries. Cut the potatoes into thin, even slices using a sharp knife or a french fry cutter. Rinse the sliced potatoes in cold water to remove any excess starch, then pat them dry with a clean kitchen towel.
In a large bowl, toss the potatoes with the potato slayer seasoning until they are evenly coated. This will help to add flavor to the fries and make them crispy when they're fried.

Using a slotted spoon, remove the fries from the oil and transfer them to a plate lined with paper towels. This will help to remove any excess oil and keep the fries crispy.

After about 30 minutes, take the prime rib out of the smoker and let it rest for about 10 minutes. This will allow the juices to redistribute throughout the meat, making it more tender and juicy when you slice it.
Using a sharp knife, slice the prime rib into thin slices, cutting against the grain. This will make the slices easier to chew and more flavorful.

Serve the sliced prime rib with the golden potato fries and a generous dollop of chimichurri sauce on the side. Chimichurri is a flavorful herb-based sauce that complements the smoky flavor of the prime rib and adds a tangy, fresh taste to the meal.

After 2 hours, spritz the ribs with a mixture of 1/4 cup apple cider vinegar and 1/4 cup apple juice to keep the meat moist: Spritzing the ribs with a mixture of apple cider vinegar and apple juice will help keep them moist and prevent them from drying out during the smoking process. Make sure to spritz them evenly and quickly to avoid losing too much heat and smoke from the smoker.

Tightly wrap the ribs in foil and place them back in the smoker for 1 to 1.5 hours, or until they feel tender: Wrapping the ribs in foil will help them retain moisture and cook more evenly. This will also help them to become more tender and juicy. Make sure to wrap them tightly and seal the edges to prevent any steam from escaping.

directions.Direction: Start off by cleaning the shrimp. Remove the outer shell and devein. Once cleaned, run shrimp under cool running water, after, lay them on paper towels and pat them really dry.
Once dried, add to a bowl. Add about 1 tbsp of oil and season with your favorite seafood seasoning, now set them aside.
Chop the parsley next, followed by the garlic. Mince the garlic well
Now heat up a skillet over medium-high heat and add 2 tbsp cooking oil. Sear shrimp, for 1 min per side, then remove them from the skillet and set them aside.
Deglaze your skillet with white wine. Then add in 1/2 cup olive oil, your heat cut it to medium-low, then add the minced garlic.

Once the garlic starts to brown, add in the parsley. Leave for 1 more minute then add in the paprika and chili flakes. (keep stirring everything so it won’t burn) Finally, add your shrimp back in and coat with the sauce and squeeze the lemon juice at the end. Cut off the heat and let cool for 3 min before serving.

Start by preparing the lobster tails. Using kitchen shears, cut along the top of the tail and pull the meat out from the shell. Be sure to remove the vein as well. Place the lobster meat on a plate and set it aside.
Take the filets and season both sides with salt and pepper. Make sure that the seasoning is evenly distributed over the surface of the meat.
Preheat a cast iron skillet on high heat. You want the skillet to be hot so that it sears the meat and locks in the flavor.

Once the skillet is hot, add the filets to the skillet and sear them for 2 minutes on one side. Flip the filets and sear them for another 2 minutes. Repeat this process for all sides. This will give the filets a nice crust and seal in the juices.
Lower the heat to low and continue to cook the filets, flipping them every minute for even cooking. This ensures that the meat cooks evenly and doesn't burn.
Once the internal temperature of the filets reaches 110°F, add the garlic butter to the skillet and baste the filets with the melted butter. This will add extra flavor and moisture to the meat.

Continue to cook the filets until they reach an internal temperature of 118°F, then remove them from the skillet and set them aside on a plate to rest. Letting the meat rest allows the juices to redistribute and ensures that the meat is tender and juicy.

While the filets are resting, add the lobster tails to the skillet and baste them with the remaining garlic butter. Cook the lobster tails for 5 minutes, turning them over halfway through the cooking process. The lobster meat should be opaque and cooked through.
In the same skillet, add the asparagus and cook until they are tender, for about 7 minutes. You can add some salt and pepper for seasoning if desired.

Once everything is cooked, slice the filets and arrange them on a serving platter along with the lobster tails and asparagus. Serve with prepared horseradish radish on the side for dipping. This tangy, spicy sauce complements the rich flavors of the meat and seafood.

directions.Direction: Soak cedar planks in water for 30 minutes to prevent the wood from catching fire and add moisture to the fish while cooking.

Preheat your smoker or grill to 225°F to create a low and slow cooking environment for the salmon.
Smoke the salmon on the cedar planks for about 20 minutes, or until the internal temperature of the fish reaches 110°F.

While the salmon is cooking, make the honey garlic sauce by combining 6 tablespoons of butter, 1/2 cup of honey, 4 teaspoons of garlic paste, and 2 teaspoons of dried dill in a small saucepan over low heat. Stir until everything is well combined and the sauce has thickened slightly.

Serve the honey garlic cedar planked salmon with the asparagus on the side for a complete and delicious meal.

directions.Direction: Preheat the grill to 350 degrees Fahrenheit. It's important to preheat the grill so that it's nice and hot when you're ready to cook the chicken wings. This will help ensure that they cook evenly and get a nice sear on the outside.

Pat the chicken wings dry with paper towels and place them in a large bowl. This step is important because it helps the seasoning adhere better to the chicken wings. Make sure to remove any excess moisture from the chicken wings before seasoning them.

Drizzle avocado oil over the chicken wings, then season generously with Smokin Buffalo blend seasoning. This seasoning blend has a nice balance of spicy and smoky flavors that pairs well with the Parmesan Garlic Sauce. Make sure to coat the chicken wings evenly with the seasoning, so that they're flavorful from the inside out.
Place the chicken wings on the preheated grill and cook for 5 minutes. This initial sear will help lock in the juices and give the chicken wings a nice crust.

Flip the wings over and continue to cook for another 5 minutes. Repeat this process until the chicken wings are cooked through and the internal temperature reaches 175 degrees Fahrenheit. Use a meat thermometer to check the internal temperature of the chicken wings, as this is the most accurate way to tell if they're fully cooked.
For the Parmesan Garlic Sauce

In a small saucepan, melt the butter over medium heat. Once the butter is melted, add garlic paste and dried parsley, and cook until fragrant, stirring occasionally. This will only take a minute or two, so make sure to keep an eye on it and don't let it burn.

Remove the saucepan from the heat and stir in freshly grated Parmesan cheese until it is melted and well-combined with the butter mixture. This will create a thick and creamy sauce that's packed with flavor.

Once the chicken wings are done cooking, transfer them to a large bowl. Pour the Parmesan Garlic Sauce over the wings and toss to coat evenly. This will ensure that every chicken wing is coated in the delicious sauce and bursting with flavor.

Serve immediately and enjoy your delicious Parmesan Garlic Grilled Chicken Wings! These wings are perfect for game day, backyard barbecues, or any occasion when you want to impress your guests with a flavorful and satisfying dish.
Preheat your grill to 350 degrees Fahrenheit. This temperature will help to ensure that the ground beef cooks evenly and the tortilla gets crispy without burning.

While the grill is heating up, let's make the chipotle mayo. In a bowl, whisk together the mayo, chipotle sauce, mustard, and smoked paprika. This will create a flavorful sauce that complements the other ingredients in the Crunchwrap. Once the sauce is well-mixed, place it in the refrigerator to chill until it's time to assemble the Crunchwraps.

Now it's time to prepare the vegetables. Slice up the lettuce and tomatoes and set them aside. You can also prepare any other vegetables or toppings you'd like to add, such as sliced avocado, diced onion, or chopped cilantro.

In another bowl, add the ground beef and taco seasoning. Make sure to mix the seasoning in thoroughly so that it is evenly distributed throughout the meat. You can use any type of taco seasoning you prefer, whether it's store-bought or homemade.
Once the grill is ready, place the patties on the grates and grill for about two minutes per side. This will ensure that the meat is cooked through but still juicy and flavorful.

Place a large skillet on the grill and add the patties to it. Use a spatula or wooden spoon to break up the ground beef into smaller pieces. This will allow it to cook more quickly and evenly. Cook the ground beef until it is crispy and well-browned, stirring occasionally to prevent sticking.

While the ground beef is cooking, warm up the large burrito tortillas slightly. You can do this by placing them directly on the grill for a few seconds on each side or by microwaving them for a few seconds.

Now it's time to assemble the Grilled Crunchwraps. Start by adding a layer of cheese on the tortilla, followed by the ground beef, chipotle mayo, tostada, lettuce, tomato, and another layer of cheese. Make sure to distribute the ingredients evenly across the tortilla and leave a bit of space around the edges to make it easier to fold.

Pinch and fold the edges of the tortilla to create a hexagonal shape. Start by folding up the bottom edge of the tortilla, then fold in the sides one at a time. Finally, fold down the top edge of the tortilla to create a complete hexagon. Make sure the edges are well-sealed so that the filling doesn't fall out while grilling.

Place the assembled Crunchwrap on the skillet and grill for about two minutes on each side or until nicely browned. Use a spatula to flip the Crunchwrap carefully and ensure that both sides are evenly cooked.

Once done, remove the Grilled Crunchwrap from the grill and allow it to cool for a minute or two before serving. You can cut it in half or into smaller pieces for easier eating. Enjoy your delicious homemade Grilled Crunchwrap!
Preheat a griddle or a large, non-stick skillet over medium heat. You want the cooking surface to be hot before you start cooking the chorizo.
Add the chorizo to the griddle and break it up into small pieces with a spatula or wooden spoon. Cook the chorizo for about 10-12 minutes, stirring occasionally, until it is browned and crispy.

While the chorizo is cooking, crack the eggs into a mixing bowl and whisk them until the whites and yolks are fully combined. Once the chorizo is crispy, push it to the sides of the griddle and add the whisked eggs to the center of the griddle.

Turn the heat to low and continue stirring the eggs and chorizo together until the eggs are fully cooked. This should take about 5-7 minutes. You can add salt and pepper to taste, but keep in mind that the chorizo is already seasoned, so you may not need much extra seasoning.
Once the chorizo and egg mixture is fully cooked, remove it from the griddle and set it aside.

Add the frozen hash browns to the griddle with about 2 tablespoons of cooking oil. Use a spatula to spread the hash browns out into an even layer. Cook the hash browns for about 4-5 minutes on one side, until they are golden brown and crispy.
Flip the hash browns over and cook for another 4-5 minutes on the other side. Once the hash browns are fully cooked, remove them from the griddle and set them aside.

Warm up the tortillas slightly, either on the griddle or in the microwave, to make them easier to fold. Place a tortilla on a clean surface and add a generous amount of shredded cheese to the center of the tortilla.

Add a generous portion of the chorizo and egg mixture on top of the cheese, followed by a drizzle of chipotle lime mayo. You can add as much or as little of the mayo as you like, depending on how spicy you like your food.
Add the hash browns on top of the mayo, followed by more shredded cheese. The cheese will help to hold the filling together and create a delicious, crispy layer on the outside of the wrap.
Fold the tortilla by grabbing one end and repeating until the filling is fully enclosed. You can use toothpicks to hold the wrap together if you like, but this step is optional.

Place the filled tortilla on the griddle with a bit of cooking oil and cook for about 2-3 minutes on each side, until the tortilla is crispy and the cheese is melted. Be sure to press down on the wrap gently with a spatula while it cooks to help the cheese melt and hold the filling together.
Once the Chorizo Crunchwrap is fully cooked and crispy, remove it from the griddle and serve immediately. Enjoy!
